Q1. What is a foreign key and what does ON DELETE CASCADE do?

A foreign key is a column used to create a relationship between two tables.
In this project:
FOREIGN KEY (user_id) REFERENCES users(id)
means every expense belongs to a valid user from the users table.
ON DELETE CASCADE means:
If a user account is deleted, all expenses related to that user are automatically deleted from the expenses table.
This prevents orphan records and keeps the database clean.


Q2. How does your backend make sure User A cannot see User B's expenses?

The backend always filters queries using:
WHERE user_id = session['user_id']
Example:
SELECT * FROM expenses
WHERE user_id=%s
When updating or deleting:
UPDATE expenses
SET title=%s
WHERE id=%s AND user_id=%s
This ensures:
•	users only access their own data 
•	one user cannot view, edit, or delete another user's expenses 
Every protected route also checks login session before processing.


Q3. What SQL query did you use for the category summary?

SELECT category,
       SUM(amount) AS total
FROM expenses
WHERE user_id=%s
GROUP BY category;
This query:
•	filters expenses for the logged-in user 
•	groups expenses by category 
•	calculates total spending per category 


Q4. What was the hardest part of this task and how did you solve it?

The hardest part was implementing secure user-based expense isolation.
The challenge was making sure:
•	users cannot access another user's expenses 
•	every API route stays protected 
This was solved by:
1.	Using Flask sessions for authentication 
2.	Checking session before every expense route 
3.	Adding: 
WHERE user_id = session['user_id']
in every SELECT, UPDATE, and DELETE query
4. Using parameterized queries for security
This ensured complete data privacy between users.
